This code provides a framework for exploring how collective memory evolves in populations. It can be adapted to various scenarios, 
including modeling memory distortion, polarization, and social dynamics. A source of noise is considered as well.
The code demonstrates two main cases:

1) A small interaction case: where the number of subjects is n=5
2) A generalization to larger interaction matrices: with n=1×10^5 subjects and a specified density density=5/n

Additionally, there are alternative options provided in the code (commented out) for further experimentation or modifications.

##

%% Symbolic setup
syms theta
Bsym = [1-theta, 0.3*theta, 0.2*theta, 0.1*theta, 0.4*theta;
        0.4*theta, 1-theta, 0.3*theta, 0.2*theta, 0.1*theta;
        0.2*theta, 0.3*theta, 1-theta, 0.3*theta, 0.2*theta;
        0, 0.2*theta, 0.4*theta, 1-theta, 0.3*theta;
        0.4*theta, 0.2*theta, 0.1*theta, 0.4*theta, 1-theta];

%% Original data
M_0 = [8 5 9;
       9 8 10;
       7 5 10;
       10 9 9;
       8 8 8];

mean_M_0 = mean(M_0);  % column-wise mean
std_M_0 = std(M_0);    % column-wise std

% Standardize
M_standardized = (M_0 - mean_M_0) ./ std_M_0;

%% Parameters
theta_val = 0.6;
T = 20;  % longer simulation to show convergence behavior
sigma_values = [0, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5];  % include larger noise

% Evaluate B(theta)
B = double(subs(Bsym, theta, theta_val));

%% Storage for plotting
num_sigmas = length(sigma_values);
M_final_all = zeros(size(M_0,1), size(M_0,2), num_sigmas);

%% Iterate over noise levels
for s = 1:num_sigmas
    sigma = sigma_values(s);
    M_t = M_standardized;
    
    for t = 1:T
        epsilon = sigma * randn(size(M_t));  % Gaussian noise
        M_t = B * M_t + epsilon;
    end
    
    % Undo standardization
    M_scores = M_t .* std_M_0 + mean_M_0;
    M_final_all(:,:,s) = M_scores;
    
    fprintf('Sigma = %.2f\n', sigma);
    disp(M_scores);
end

